Azure DevOps is a suite of five integrated developer services that cover the full software delivery lifecycle. Azure Repos provides unlimited private Git repositories. Azure Pipelines provides C-I-C-D — the ability to build, test, and deploy any language to any platform. Azure Boards provides agile project management with epics, user stories, tasks, and sprints. Azure Test Plans supports manual and exploratory testing with full traceability to work items. Azure Artifacts provides private package feeds for N-u-Get, npm, Maven, Python, and Universal Packages. The A-W-S equivalent combines CodeCommit, CodeBuild, CodePipeline, and CodeArtifact — Azure DevOps packages all of this into a single integrated product. GitHub Actions is the alternative C-I-C-D platform for teams hosting code on GitHub, and it has deep integration with Azure deployment targets.

Let us start with Azure Pipelines and its core concepts.

A pipeline is defined in a Y-A-M-L file — typically named azure-pipelines dot yml — stored at the root of the repository. The structure has four levels. At the top is the pipeline itself. Inside the pipeline are stages — logical phases such as Build, Test, Deploy to Dev, and Deploy to Production. Inside each stage are jobs. A job runs on a single agent machine and its steps execute sequentially. Inside each job are steps, which are either tasks — pre-built actions from the marketplace — or scripts — inline shell or PowerShell commands. Stages run sequentially by default, but you can parallelise them using the dependsOn keyword. Jobs within a stage can run in parallel automatically.

There are three types of agents. Microsoft-hosted agents provision a fresh virtual machine for every pipeline run using standard images such as ubuntu-latest, windows-latest, or macos-latest. They include common build tools pre-installed and require zero maintenance. Self-hosted agents are machines you register with Azure DevOps — they can run on V-Ms, containers, or physical servers. Because they persist between runs, build times are faster and you can install custom software or access private networks. Scale-set agents use an Azure virtual machine scale set as an agent pool — Azure DevOps automatically scales the pool up and down based on pipeline demand, combining the convenience of managed agents with the customisation of self-hosted agents.

Variables in Azure Pipelines have several forms. Pipeline variables are defined inline in the Y-A-M-L file or in the pipeline settings in the portal. Variable groups are reusable collections of variables defined once in the Library and referenced by multiple pipelines. The most important pattern for secrets is Key Vault-linked variable groups — the variable group is backed directly by an Azure Key Vault, and secrets are fetched at pipeline runtime using the service connection's managed identity. The secrets are never stored in Azure DevOps. Secret variables are masked in all pipeline logs and are never exposed to jobs triggered by forked pull requests.

Now let us look at what a C-I pipeline does.

A Continuous Integration pipeline runs automatically on every push and every pull request to validate that the code is correct before it is merged. A typical C-I pipeline has five steps. First it restores dependencies — pip install, npm ci, dotnet restore, or maven install. Second it builds the application — compiling code, transpiling, or packaging. Third it runs unit tests and publishes the results. Azure Pipelines can display test pass and fail trends over time and track code coverage percentages. Fourth it runs security scanning — tools like Credential Scanner detect accidentally committed secrets, and tools like Snyk or Pip Audit detect known vulnerabilities in dependencies. Fifth it publishes a build artifact — the Docker image, application ZIP, or J-A-R file that the deployment stages will use.

The Cache task is important for keeping C-I builds fast on Microsoft-hosted agents. It stores and restores directories between runs, keyed by a hash of the dependency lock file. When the lock file has not changed, the cache is restored and the dependency download step is skipped entirely.

Branch policies in Azure Repos enforce quality gates on protected branches. You can require a minimum number of reviewer approvals, a passing build validation pipeline, linked work items, and resolution of all review comments before a pull request can be completed. These policies make it impossible to bypass the C-I pipeline and push broken code directly to main.

Now let us look at C-D pipelines — Continuous Delivery and Deployment.

An Environment in Azure Pipelines is a named deployment target — dev, staging, or production — that tracks deployment history and hosts approval checks. Every pipeline run that deploys to an environment is recorded in a timeline, showing which version was deployed, when, by whom, and whether it succeeded. For Kubernetes targets, the environment also shows live pod and workload status. Approval checks on the production environment require one or more named approvers to explicitly approve before the deployment proceeds. Other check types include an Azure Monitor alert check that holds the deployment until there are no active alerts on specified resources, a REST A-P-I check that calls an external endpoint, a required template check that enforces the use of a specific approved pipeline template, and a business hours gate that restricts deployments to specific times.

Deployment strategies control how a new version replaces the old one. The runOnce strategy deploys to all targets simultaneously and is appropriate for dev and test environments. The rolling strategy replaces instances in batches — for example 20 percent at a time — so some instances are always available during the deployment. The canary strategy routes a small percentage of traffic to the new version first, validates it with real traffic, then completes the rollout. The blue-green strategy maintains two identical environments and swaps traffic between them — the old environment remains live until the swap, providing instant rollback.

A service connection authenticates the pipeline to an external service. For Azure deployments, the best practice is to use Workload Identity Federation for the service connection. This means the service connection is backed by an app registration in Entra I-D with federated credentials that trust tokens issued by Azure DevOps. No client secret is stored anywhere in Azure DevOps — the pipeline exchanges its own identity token for an Entra I-D access token at runtime. This eliminates the risk of leaked service principal credentials.

Let us now look at deploying to specific Azure targets.

For App Service, the AzureWebApp task deploys a Z-I-P package, a container image, or a J-A-R file. The recommended pattern for zero-downtime deployments uses deployment slots. The pipeline deploys to the staging slot, runs smoke tests against the staging U-R-L, and then performs a slot swap that promotes staging to production. If something goes wrong, swapping back takes seconds.

For containerised workloads, the Docker task builds and pushes an image to Azure Container Registry with a tag derived from the build I-D, ensuring every build produces a uniquely tagged image. The KubernetesManifest task then applies Kubernetes manifests to an A-K-S cluster, substituting the new image tag. Helm deployments use the HelmDeploy task to run helm upgrade install with per-environment values overrides.

For infrastructure as code, the AzureResourceManagerTemplateDeployment task deploys Bicep or A-R-M templates. For Terraform, the TerraformTaskV4 extension task runs init, plan, and apply. Terraform state is stored in an Azure Blob Storage container with state locking via blob leases — this is the standard pattern for team-based Terraform on Azure.

Now let us look at GitHub Actions for Azure.

GitHub Actions workflows are Y-A-M-L files stored in the dot github slash workflows directory of a GitHub repository. The concepts map directly to Azure Pipelines: a workflow is a pipeline, a job is a job, a step is a step, an action is a task, and a runner is an agent. GitHub Actions environments support required reviewers — the equivalent of Azure Pipelines approval gates.

The recommended authentication method from GitHub Actions to Azure is OpenID Connect, following the same Workload Identity Federation principle. You create an app registration in Entra I-D with a federated credential that trusts GitHub's OpenID Connect issuer for a specific repository and branch. In the workflow, the azure login action exchanges the GitHub-issued identity token for an Entra I-D access token — no long-lived client secret is ever stored in GitHub Secrets. The secrets stored in GitHub are only the client I-D, tenant I-D, and subscription I-D — none of these alone are sensitive credentials.

Azure provides first-class GitHub Actions for every deployment target: azure slash webapps-deploy for App Service, azure slash functions-action for Azure Functions, azure slash aks-set-context and azure slash k8s-deploy for A-K-S, and azure slash arm-deploy for Bicep and A-R-M templates.

Let us cover pipeline security best practices.

Never put secrets in Y-A-M-L files or repository code. Link variable groups to Azure Key Vault so secrets are fetched at runtime. Use Workload Identity Federation for all service connections to eliminate stored credentials. Pin third-party pipeline tasks and GitHub Actions to a specific commit S-H-A rather than a mutable version tag — a tag like v1 can be reassigned by the publisher to point at different code. Use Azure Artifacts upstream sources to proxy and cache public package registries — this gives you an audit trail of every package version used and protects against packages being removed or tampered with on the public registry. Run dependency vulnerability scanners such as pip-audit or npm audit in C-I. Enable Credential Scanner in Azure Pipelines to catch accidentally committed secrets before they reach the repository history. Use protected resources so that only specific approved pipelines can access production service connections and variable groups. Require pull request reviews and passing build validation before merging to main — this makes the C-I pipeline the mandatory gate for all code changes.

To summarise. Azure DevOps provides an integrated suite covering repositories, pipelines, boards, test plans, and package feeds. Pipelines are structured as stages, jobs, and steps, running on Microsoft-hosted or self-hosted agents. C-I pipelines validate every change with builds, tests, and security scans. C-D pipelines use Environments with approval checks and deployment strategies to safely promote changes through dev, staging, and production. Use Workload Identity Federation for all service connections — never store client secrets in Azure DevOps or GitHub Secrets. Link variable groups to Azure Key Vault for runtime secret injection. Use slot swaps for zero-downtime App Service deployments. Store Terraform state in Azure Blob Storage. Pin third-party tasks to S-H-A hashes and use Azure Artifacts to proxy public registries for a secure supply chain.

In the next topic, we will look at Azure Cost Management and pricing — how to understand your Azure bill, set budgets and alerts, and optimise your spending.
